1. 5 IT Job Roles
-> Full-Stack Developer: Builds and maintains both the front-end (user interface) and back-end (server and database) of a website or application.

-> Data Analyst: Examines raw data sets to find trends, create visualizations, and help businesses make informed decisions.

-> DevOps Engineer: Bridges the gap between development and operations teams by automating workflows and managing infrastructure for faster software delivery.

-> UI/UX Designer: Designs the visual layout and user experience of a digital product to ensure it is intuitive, accessible, and attractive.

-> Cybersecurity Analyst: Monitors networks and systems to protect an organization's digital assets from cyber threats and security breaches.

2. Product vs. Service Companies
Product Companies (Build and sell their own software/goods)
-> Adobe: Creates and sells specialized creative software packages, such as Photoshop and Illustrator, for digital content creators.

-> Microsoft: Develops and licenses the Windows operating system and productivity software like Microsoft 365.

-> Netflix: Operates a proprietary subscription-based streaming platform and builds the technology to deliver video content globally.

Service Companies (Provide custom IT expertise and client-based solutions)
-> TCS (Tata Consultancy Services): Builds custom banking software systems and manages IT infrastructure for global financial institutions.

-> Infosys: Offers cloud migration services and manages digital transformation projects for retail and healthcare clients.

-> Accenture: Provides specialized tech consulting, helping enterprises integrate complex corporate software systems like SAP or Salesforce.

3. Tech Tools & Concepts
GitHub: (Global Information Tracker Hub) A cloud-based platform used by developers to store, manage, track, and collaborate on software code.

-> Slack: (Searchable Log of All Conversation and Knowledge) A business communication platform designed for team messaging, file sharing, and workspace collaboration.

-> Jira: (Derived from "Gojira") An agile project management tool used by teams to plan, track, and manage software development issues and bugs.

-> IDE: (Integrated Development Environment) A software application that provides a comprehensive environment featuring a code editor, debugger, and build automation tools for programmers.

-> API: (Application Programming Interface) A set of protocols that allows different software applications to communicate and share data with one another.

4. 5 Programming Languages & Use Cases
-> Python: Widely used as the primary language for training machine learning models and analyzing large data sets.

-> JavaScript: The foundational language used to build interactive features, animations, and dynamic behavior on modern websites.

-> Java: Popularly used to build robust, highly secure backend enterprise applications and legacy banking systems.

-> PHP: Commonly used for server-side web development to power content management systems like WordPress.

-> C++: Frequently utilized in high-performance application development, such as game engines and operating systems, due to its speed and direct hardware control.

5. Developer vs. Tester
-> A developer focuses on writing, building, and implementing the source code to create functional software features based on project requirements. Conversely, a tester strategically executes and evaluates that software to identify bugs, vulnerabilities, and defects before it reaches the end user.
